
@startuml

' Define classes with attributes

class Provider {
    - name: String
    - location: String
}

class Cruise {
    - cruiseNumber: int
    - name: String
    - startDate: Date
    - endDate: Date
    - destinationArea: DestinationArea
}

class Employee {
    - name: String
    - socialSecurityNumber: String
}

class Guest {
    - name: String
    - isVIP: boolean
}

class Ship {
    - name: String
    - numberOfDecks: int
    - length: double
    - maxPassengers: int
}

class TravelAgency {
    - name: String
    - address: String
}

class Booking {
    - bookingNumber: String
    - bookingDate: Date
}

class DestinationArea {
    - name: String
    - seaName: String
}

class Show {
    - title: String
    - duration: int  // in minutes
}

class Ticket {
    - ticketId: int
}

' Relationships

Provider "1" -- "many" Cruise : organizes
Cruise "1" -- "many" Employee : requires
Cruise "1" -- "many" Guest : has
Cruise "1" -- "1" Ship : uses
Cruise "1" -- "many" Show : offers
Cruise "1" -- "1" DestinationArea : heads to
TravelAgency "1" -- "many" Booking : handles
Booking "1" -- "1" Cruise : for
Booking "1" -- "1" Guest : by
Ticket "1" -- "1" Cruise : belongs to
Guest "0..*" -- "0..*" Cruise : participates in
Guest "0..*" -- "0..*" Ticket : owns (1 per cruise)

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Points:
- **Multiplicity**: Indicated where necessary (e.g., `0..*` means zero or more).
- **Aggregation/Composition**: Not explicitly shown, but you can infer some composition (e.g., a `Cruise` **composes** a `Ticket`).
- **Uniqueness Constraints**:
  - Each `Ticket` belongs to **exactly one** `Cruise`.
  - A `Guest` may have **multiple tickets**, but only **one per cruise**.
- **Inheritance**: Not needed in this case; all are simple value-based classes.

